{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500140"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:09:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:09:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1613"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582965"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:02:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:02:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1613"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1613"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.58,0.08,0.02,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1613"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109741"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1613","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1613"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1613"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92140"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"493"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"9735"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3653"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16134"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41139"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42353"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109741","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109741"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of shortness of breath on exertion and palpitations. He also reports occasional lightheadedness but no loss of consciousness or chest pain. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He is a retired truck driver and consumes minimal alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 150/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Cardiovascular examination reveals a regular tachycardia with no murmurs. Chest is clear to auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn ECG is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atrial fibrillation","Atrial flutter","Ventricular tachycardia","Ventricular fibrillation","Sinus tachycardia"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ECG shows a regular, narrow-complex tachycardia at 150/min with sawtooth P waves (see blue circle in annotated ECG below), characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Eatrial flutter\u003C/strong\u003E. The sawtooth pattern represents organised atrial activity at approximately 300/min with 2:1 atrioventricular conduction, resulting in the ventricular rate of 150/min. There is also poor R wave progression, suggesting possible prior anterior myocardial infarction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrial fibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E would present as an irregularly irregular rhythm with absent P waves and fibrillatory waves, rather than the regular rhythm with organised atrial activity seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E is a broad complex tachycardia (QRS \u0026gt;120 ms or three small squares) arising from the ventricles. This ECG shows narrow QRS complexes, excluding ventricular tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentricular fibrillation\u003C/strong\u003E is a life-threatening arrhythmia characterised by chaotic electrical activity with no discernible QRS complexes. The patient would be unconscious and pulseless, which is incompatible with this clinical presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESinus tachycardia\u003C/strong\u003E would show normal P waves preceding each QRS complex with a 1:1 relationship. The sawtooth pattern and 2:1 conduction seen here are not consistent with sinus tachycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAtrial flutter results from a macro-reentrant circuit, typically in the right atrium. The classic ventricular rate of 150/min occurs because the refractory period of the AV node limits conduction. Rate control can be achieved with AV nodal blocking agents such as beta-blockers or calcium channel blockers. Haemodynamically unstable patients require synchronised DC cardioversion. Like atrial fibrillation, atrial flutter carries a risk of thromboembolic complications, and anticoagulation should be considered based on stroke risk assessment. Definitive treatment often involves catheter ablation of the re-entrant circuit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Atrial flutter is characterised by sawtooth P waves on ECG and typically presents with a ventricular rate of 150/min due to 2:1 AV conduction.","Atrial flutter is a regular narrow complex tachycardia arising from organised re-entrant circuits in the atria.","Both atrial flutter and atrial fibrillation require anticoagulation assessment due to risk of thromboembolic complications."],"references":["Hindricks et al, ESC Scientific Document Group, 2020 ESC Guidelines for the diagnosis and management of atrial fibrillation developed in collaboration with the European Association for Cardio-Thoracic Surgery (EACTS): The Task Force for the diagnosis and management of atrial fibrillation of the European Society of Cardiology (ESC), European Heart Journal, Volume 42, Issue 5, 1 February 2021, Pages 373\u2013498, https://doi.org/10.1093/eurheartj/ehaa612."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92140"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1613"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21097"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21972"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21097"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rRouYhTOg0YQ9loqkv4h0nQcqr37Y8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/rRouYhTOg0YQ9loqkv4h0nQcqr37Y8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":363}},{"type":"media","id":"21972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21972"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xS1KKzeuEtTtscVhVSGwbPu4RFpMM5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/xS1KKzeuEtTtscVhVSGwbPu4RFpMM5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":363}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92140","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92140"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-25T21:08:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-25T21:09:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1613"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109741"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji"